---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import CtaButton from "../components/CtaButton.astro";

const slashingMath = `# Indicative slashing schedule (pallet-slashing, at-launch parameters)

# Soft fault (single sampling mismatch on a low-stakes request)
slash = min(stake * 0.005, 25 OROG)
reputation_decay = -50 points

# Hard fault (repeated mismatches OR opML challenge resolves against operator)
slash = min(stake * 0.10, full_stake)
reputation_decay = -500 points

# Severe fault (coldkey duplication, fraudulent attestation, signed-receipt forgery)
slash = full_stake
ban_duration = 90 days
governance_review = required (publish dispute panel verdict on-chain)`;
---

<Base
  title="Validators"
  description="Validators on Orogen sample-replay 1–5% of jobs on identical attested hardware. Yuma-style consensus, 10× operator-min stake, slashing math, and a hard separation between validators and the foundation-run validator-watcher set."
  path="/validators"
>
  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">For validators</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">Validators are GPU operators with a different job.</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      A validator runs the same hardware as a dc-standard or dc-premium
      operator — but instead of serving customer inference, they pull a 1–5%
      sample of finalised jobs and replay them. If the replay output disagrees
      with the operator's signed receipt, the validator raises a challenge.
      Disagreement is the signal; consensus over many validators is the
      arbitrator.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">The role</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Replay, not consensus on weights.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Orogen validators do not vote on model outputs. They <em>replay</em>
        them. The replay is bit-exact when (a) the operator runs in
        deterministic-kernel mode and (b) the validator runs the same model and
        adapter on equivalent hardware. The protocol pays the validator out of
        the 15% verification slice in proportion to (replays performed) ×
        (consensus alignment with the majority replay outcome).
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        This is the Yuma-style design from Bittensor's verifiable-work pattern,
        applied to actual inference work rather than to subnet-defined miner
        scoring. The crucial difference: the validator's score is derived from a
        physical replay event with a verifiable input/output pair, not from a
        subjective evaluation rubric.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Replay sampling (RFC-0006)</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">How the sample is drawn.</h2>
    <ol class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-crust-200">
      <li class="rounded-md border border-crust-800 bg-crust-900/50 px-4 py-3">
        <strong class="text-crust-100">VRF-seeded.</strong> Each epoch (~72 minutes), the chain produces a VRF output that seeds a
        per-validator sampling schedule. The seed is unpredictable to operators ahead of time, preventing targeted optimisation.
      </li>
      <li class="rounded-md border border-crust-800 bg-crust-900/50 px-4 py-3">
        <strong class="text-crust-100">Tier-weighted.</strong> Sampling rate is 1–5% at dc-premium/dc-standard, 5–10% at
        cloud-rented, and 10%+ at prosumer. Edge and embed-only tiers are stake-only — they are not sampled but their stake is at risk for fraud disputes.
      </li>
      <li class="rounded-md border border-crust-800 bg-crust-900/50 px-4 py-3">
        <strong class="text-crust-100">Quote-bound.</strong> The validator fetches the receipt's
        (model_hash, adapter_hash, prompt_hash, output_hash, attestation_quote, nonce) tuple from the chain commitment, pulls the corresponding weights from the content-addressed CDN, and replays.
      </li>
      <li class="rounded-md border border-crust-800 bg-crust-900/50 px-4 py-3">
        <strong class="text-crust-100">Match or challenge.</strong> Exact-match output_hash → finalisation. Mismatch → opML L5 challenge window opens; other validators are invited to replay; bisection narrows the divergent layer; dispute panel renders the slashing verdict.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-crust-500">
      RFC-0006 is the formal specification. Full text at <a class="underline" href="https://docs.orogen.network">docs.orogen.network</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Stake requirements</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">10× the operator minimum.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Validators must hold 10× the operator-min stake for the tier they
        sample. At launch parameters: 5,000 OROG to sample dc-premium, 1,000
        OROG to sample dc-standard, 500 OROG to sample cloud-rented, 250 OROG
        to sample prosumer. Validator stake is also slashable — for a missed
        challenge, for a false-positive challenge raised against a correct
        operator, and (severely) for collusion with a sampled operator.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Validators do <em>not</em> earn yield for passive holding. The 15%
        verification slice is paid out per epoch in proportion to replays
        actually performed (with consensus alignment as a multiplier). A
        validator with stake but no replay activity earns zero. This is the
        Bittensor 41/41/18 model inverted: the protocol pays validators for
        verifiable work, not for being present.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Yuma scoring</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Validator-vs-validator consensus.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      For each replay, the validator submits (job_id, replayed_output_hash,
      decision ∈ &#123;match, mismatch&#125;). The chain computes per-epoch consensus:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-4 max-w-3xl list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-crust-200">
      <li><strong class="text-crust-100">Match weight.</strong> Validators whose decision aligns with the dispute-panel-finalised outcome receive full weight for that replay.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-crust-100">Disagreement decay.</strong> A validator who repeatedly disagrees with the consensus (i.e. raises false-positive challenges) sees their Yuma weight decay, which reduces their share of the 15% verification slice.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-crust-100">Collusion resistance.</strong> The dispute panel can promote any sampled replay to an N-of-M re-execution by independent validators if cluster-correlation suggests stake-weighted collusion. This is the Bittensor SN-based defence repurposed for replay sampling.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Slashing math</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Three fault classes.</h2>

      <CodeBlock code={slashingMath} lang="python" filename="slashing.py (pseudocode)" />

      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Slashed stake is burned at the chain level (it is not redistributed to
        the challenger). This avoids the well-known incentive misalignment where
        challengers profit from false positives; the only reward for raising a
        valid challenge is the reputation gain and the share of the 15%
        verification slice earned through Yuma-weighted replays.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Validator-vs-watcher separation</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Two roles, two stake pools, two reward streams.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      The protocol distinguishes between <strong class="text-crust-100">validators</strong>
      — permissionless, stake-bonded, paid from the verification slice — and
      <strong class="text-crust-100">validator-watchers</strong>, a smaller
      foundation-and-DAO-operated set that runs opML challenge bisection and
      arbitrates the dispute panel.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      The separation is deliberate. Validators have a real economic incentive to
      do the work but not to render final slashing verdicts on each other.
      Watchers handle the arbitration step, can override a clearly-incorrect
      validator consensus, and are themselves bonded with a much larger stake
      (50,000 OROG at-launch parameter). The watcher set rotates governance-set;
      its decisions are appealable to on-chain governance.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      On the post-mainnet roadmap, the watcher set opens to permissionless
      entry (with the larger stake and a 6-month observation period before
      earning the full reward slice). Until then, watcher operation, public
      decision logs, and on-chain audit trails are Forge/mainnet readiness
      items rather than live public services.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <CtaButton href="/downloads" variant="primary">Artifact policy</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="https://docs.orogen.network" variant="secondary" rel="noopener noreferrer">RFC-0006 (replay sampling)</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="/operators" variant="ghost">Operator role</CtaButton>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
